<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="69" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,260,1149]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[200,320,764,789]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gonçalves &amp; Souto &amp; Mermudes &amp; Silveira, 2019" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Souto &amp; Mermudes &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2019" box="[330,575,765,788]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Uanauna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angaporan" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[330,575,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Uanauna angaporan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[584,680,764,789]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[584,680,764,789]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
occurs on the coastal mountains of the Serra do Mar mountain range, in the South Fluminense region, at leastb from latitudes 23°95’ to 23°13’ All specimens were collected in Submontane and Montane regions: at the Tijuca National Park, by Alvarenga e Seabra col., (with no detailed information of elevation); at Parque Estadual Cunhambebe, at 
<quantity box="[991,1069,871,896]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" unit="m" value="150.0">150 m</quantity>
; and at 
<collectingCountry box="[1161,1207,871,896]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Ilha</collectingCountry>
Grande State Park, from 
<quantity box="[216,291,908,933]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.36" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" unit="m" value="336.0">336 m</quantity>
to 
<specimenCount box="[332,415,908,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" type="generic">
<quantity box="[332,411,908,933]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.659999999999999" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" unit="m" value="666.0">666 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
Individuals were collected between August and September—at the end of winter and the beginning of spring, when temperatures are around 22°C and rainfall is relatively lower (in 9 collections during a 59-year interval, the first being in 1958 and the last one in 2017). Therefore, it seems that this species are univoltine swarmers, as many other fireflies (e.g. 
<emphasis box="[812,1070,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Scissicauda disjuncta</emphasis>
; cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Silveira, L. F. L. &amp; Mermudes, J. R. M. &amp; Bocakova, M." box="[1132,1387,1015,1040]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" pagination="55" refId="ref8259" refString="Silveira, L. F. L., Mermudes, J. R. M. &amp; Bocakova, M. (2016 b) Systematic review of the firefly genus Scissicauda (Coleoptera, Lampyridae, Amydetinae) from Brazil. ZooKeys, 558, 55. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 558.6040" type="journal article" year="2016">
Silveira 
<emphasis box="[1235,1291,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">et al</emphasis>
. 2016b
</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, even with few individuals found on the continental island of 
<collectingCountry box="[1009,1055,1052,1077]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Ilha</collectingCountry>
Grande, a small morphological variation is evident between two populations, such as elitral coloration (overall darker in PEIG individuals) and small marginal nuances in the shape of the sternum IX.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2636246/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" startId="9.[151,264,1633,1655]" targetBox="[422,1147,1218,1593]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1633,1685]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,341,1633,1655]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">FIGURES 29–31.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gonçalves &amp; Souto &amp; Mermudes &amp; Silveira, 2019" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Souto &amp; Mermudes &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2019" box="[356,568,1634,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Uanauna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angaporan" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[356,568,1634,1655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Uanauna angaporan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[576,660,1633,1655]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[576,660,1633,1655]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
: 29–31, abdomen, 29, lateral; 30, ventral; 31, oblique. Scale bar:1mm (29– 31).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1730,1971]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">
The two population spots of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gonçalves &amp; Souto &amp; Mermudes &amp; Silveira, 2019" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Souto &amp; Mermudes &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2019" box="[536,780,1731,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Uanauna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angaporan" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[536,780,1731,1754]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Uanauna angaporan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[787,881,1730,1755]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[787,881,1730,1755]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
are geographically isolated from each other by the sea: one on the mainland, on the coast of Rio de Janeiro and the other on 
<collectingCountry box="[1076,1122,1766,1791]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Ilha</collectingCountry>
Grande (in this case, only four individuals were found, only one of these is male), also in the Rio de Janeiro state. The level of genetic isolation of these populations remains unknown. However, the two populations are likely isolated to some degree, given their characteristics typical of poor dispersers (e.g. small size, reduced crossvein), associated with those of assortative mating, evinced by the unique modifications of the terminalia (
<bibRefCitation author="Panhuis, T. M. &amp; Butlin, R. &amp; Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T." box="[1198,1431,1910,1935]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" pagination="364 - 371" refId="ref7852" refString="Panhuis, T. M., Butlin, R., Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T. (2001) Sexual selection and speciation. Trends in Ecology &amp; Evolution, 16 (7), 364 - 371. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0169 - 5347 (01) 02160 - 7" type="journal article" year="2001">
Panhuis 
<emphasis box="[1300,1361,1910,1934]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Silveira, L. &amp; Khattar, G. &amp; Souto, P. &amp; Mermudes, J. R. M. &amp; Takiya, D. M. &amp; Monteiro, R. F." box="[151,393,1946,1971]" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" pagination="371 - 384" refId="ref8184" refString="Silveira, L., Khattar, G., Souto, P., Mermudes, J. R. M., Takiya, D. M. &amp; Monteiro, R. F. (2016 a) Integrative taxonomy of new firefly taxa from the Atlantic Rainforest. Systematics and Biodiversity, 14 (4), 371 - 384. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2016.1153006" type="journal article" year="2016">
Silveira 
<emphasis box="[250,309,1946,1970]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">et al.</emphasis>
2016a
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,151,608]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
Terminal abdominal modifications have been proposed to promote reproductive isolation (
<bibRefCitation author="Silveira, L. &amp; Khattar, G. &amp; Souto, P. &amp; Mermudes, J. R. M. &amp; Takiya, D. M. &amp; Monteiro, R. F." pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="371 - 384" refId="ref8184" refString="Silveira, L., Khattar, G., Souto, P., Mermudes, J. R. M., Takiya, D. M. &amp; Monteiro, R. F. (2016 a) Integrative taxonomy of new firefly taxa from the Atlantic Rainforest. Systematics and Biodiversity, 14 (4), 371 - 384. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2016.1153006" type="journal article" year="2016">
Silveira 
<emphasis box="[1375,1428,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">et al</emphasis>
. 2016a
</bibRefCitation>
), favoring the accumulation of independent anagenesis in parapatric populations, thus promoting speciation (
<bibRefCitation author="Panhuis, T. M. &amp; Butlin, R. &amp; Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T." box="[285,515,223,248]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="364 - 371" refId="ref7852" refString="Panhuis, T. M., Butlin, R., Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T. (2001) Sexual selection and speciation. Trends in Ecology &amp; Evolution, 16 (7), 364 - 371. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0169 - 5347 (01) 02160 - 7" type="journal article" year="2001">
Panhuis 
<emphasis box="[386,445,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
). However, it must be noted that models of structural mechanisms of lock-andkey reproductive isolation have been supplanted by the sensory lock-and-key model in the literature. The latter is supposedly more common and effective in avoiding hybridization during reinforcement upon secondary contact (
<bibRefCitation author="Masly, J. P." box="[385,536,332,357]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref7608" refString="Masly, J. P. (2012) 170 years of &quot; lock-and-key &quot;: genital morphology and reproductive isolation. International Journal of Evolutionary Biology, 2012, 1 - 11. https: // doi. org / 10.1155 / 2012 / 247352" type="journal article" year="2012">Masly 2012</bibRefCitation>
). Nevertheless, the primary role of sensorial lock-and-key mechanisms in driving reproductive isolation has been challenged due to lack of evidence (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Arnqvist, G." box="[1112,1286,367,392]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="784" refId="ref6539" refString="Arnqvist, G. (1998) Comparative evidence for the evolution of genitalia by sexual selection. Nature, 393 (6687), 784. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / 31689" type="journal article" year="1998">Arnqvist 1998</bibRefCitation>
). Otherwise, there is increasing evidence that selection is an important factor prior to genital morphological variation (
<bibRefCitation author="Arnqvist, G." box="[159,337,439,464]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="784" refId="ref6539" refString="Arnqvist, G. (1998) Comparative evidence for the evolution of genitalia by sexual selection. Nature, 393 (6687), 784. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / 31689" type="journal article" year="1998">Arnqvist 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Panhuis, T. M. &amp; Butlin, R. &amp; Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T." box="[353,593,439,464]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="364 - 371" refId="ref7852" refString="Panhuis, T. M., Butlin, R., Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T. (2001) Sexual selection and speciation. Trends in Ecology &amp; Evolution, 16 (7), 364 - 371. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0169 - 5347 (01) 02160 - 7" type="journal article" year="2001">
Panhuis 
<emphasis box="[457,512,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">et al</emphasis>
. 2001
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ritchie, M. G." box="[609,769,439,464]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="79 - 102" refId="ref7999" refString="Ritchie, M. G. (2007) Sexual selection and speciation. Annual Review of Ecology, Evolution, and Systematics, 38, 79 - 102. https: // doi. org / 10.1146 / annurev. ecolsys. 38.091206.095733" type="journal article" year="2007">Ritchie 2007</bibRefCitation>
), that is: instead of guiding genital diversification, the reproductive isolation is actually a product of sexual selection (
<bibRefCitation author="Panhuis, T. M. &amp; Butlin, R. &amp; Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T." box="[899,1132,476,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="364 - 371" refId="ref7852" refString="Panhuis, T. M., Butlin, R., Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T. (2001) Sexual selection and speciation. Trends in Ecology &amp; Evolution, 16 (7), 364 - 371. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0169 - 5347 (01) 02160 - 7" type="journal article" year="2001">
Panhuis 
<emphasis box="[1001,1053,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">et al</emphasis>
. 2001
</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, 
<bibRefCitation author="Panhuis, T. M. &amp; Butlin, R. &amp; Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T." pageId="10" pageNumber="69" pagination="364 - 371" refId="ref7852" refString="Panhuis, T. M., Butlin, R., Zuk, M. &amp; Tregenza, T. (2001) Sexual selection and speciation. Trends in Ecology &amp; Evolution, 16 (7), 364 - 371. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0169 - 5347 (01) 02160 - 7" type="journal article" year="2001">
Panhuis 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">et al.</emphasis>
(2001)
</bibRefCitation>
suggest that sexual selection favors allopatric speciation. In this context, 
<taxonomicName authority="Gonçalves &amp; Souto &amp; Mermudes &amp; Silveira, 2019" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Souto &amp; Mermudes &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2019" box="[1163,1271,513,536]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Uanauna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1163,1271,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Uanauna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1281,1394,511,536]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1281,1394,511,536]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">gen. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, as well as other poor-dispersing fireflies with stereotypic terminalia, emerge as promising model systems in the study of speciation and biogeography.
</paragraph>
